data.content:
Your test works but has weak assertions — every check uses `Assert.IsTrue`, which gives unhelpful failure messages like "Expected: True, Actual: False". MSTest has dedicated APIs for this.

**Use `CollectionAssert` and specific assertions:**

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Count — gives actual value on failure
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // All items satisfy a condition
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), 
        "Expected all users to be active");

    // Contains an item matching a condition
    Assert.IsTrue(users.Any(u => u.Role == "Admin"), 
        "Expected an Admin user");
}
```

**Key improvements:**

| Before | After | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count > 0)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, x.Count)` | Shows expected vs actual count |
| `Assert.IsTrue(admin != null)` | `Assert.IsTrue(..., "message")` | Always add failure messages to `IsTrue` |
| `users.Single()` throwing | `Assert.IsTrue(users.Any(...))` | Avoids `InvalidOperationException` masking the real failure |

**Other `CollectionAssert` methods worth knowing:**

```csharp
// Verify exact contents (order-insensitive)
CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual);

// Verify exact contents + order
CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual);

// Check membership
CollectionAssert.Contains(users, expectedUser);

// All items are of a type
CollectionAssert.AllAreSatisfied(users, u => Assert.IsTrue(u.IsActive));

// No nulls
CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);

// All unique
CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreUnique(users);
```

**Rule of thumb:** avoid bare `Assert.IsTrue` for collection checks — use `Assert.AreEqual` for values, `CollectionAssert` for collection-specific logic, and always include a failure message when `IsTrue` is unavoidable.
